  "prompt": "What is the most frightening (not most grotesque) horror movie of all time? And why?",
  "response": "This is subjective, but many film critics and horror fans consider \"The Exorcist\" (1973) to be the most genuinely frightening horror movie. Directed by William Friedkin, the film is terrifying for several psychological reasons:\n\n1. It deals with demonic possession, which taps into deeply rooted cultural and religious fears\n2. The realistic performances make the supernatural events feel disturbingly plausible\n3. The gradual transformation of a young girl into something inhuman is psychologically traumatic\n4. The film suggests evil can randomly strike innocent victims\n5. It challenges religious faith and the concept of good vs. evil\n6. The sound design and subtle visual effects create an overwhelming sense of dread\n\nOther films often mentioned as deeply frightening include:\n- \"Hereditary\" (2018)\n- \"The Shining\" (1980)\n- \"Rosemary's Baby\" (1968)\n- \"The Blair Witch Project\" (1999)\n\nThe \"most frightening\" movie often depends on individual psychological triggers, personal fears, and cultural background. What terrifies one person might not affect another in the same way.\n\nWould you be interested in hearing more about why \"The Exorcist\" is considered so psychologically disturbing?",
